data.title: Kenosha County prepares for four-day mega music fest Country Thunder opening July 18
data.meta_description: Mid-July, sweltering temperatures, rainy days and mud.
data.text:
Mid-July, sweltering temperatures, rainy days and mud.

That means it’s time for Wisconsin’s largest country music festival, which calls Kenosha County its home each year for four days. This year Country Thunder takes place Thursday, July 18 and runs through Sunday, July 21.

But preparations for Country Thunder are made months in advance and promoters and local authorities continued to ready the grounds for the 30,000 people who will be on site each day at the 37-acre Shadow Hill Ranch, 2305 Lance Drive, in the Town of Randall. The campgrounds and parking open at 9 a.m., Wednesday, July 17. The concert and festival grounds will be open at 2 p.m. on Thursday and at 1 p.m. the remaining three days. Closing time for the festival grounds have moved up an hour this year to 1 a.m. from 2 a.m. last year.

This year’s lineup shines the spotlight on some of country’s hottest stars headlining nightly shows including Eric Church, Lainey Wilson, Koe Wetzel and Bailey Zimmerman.

New to the event’s mainstage and also headlining performances is the Canadian rock band Nickleback, according to event spokesperson Megan Benoit.

“We’ve got a rock band this year, Nickleback, which is not the norm,” she said. The nightly lineup can be found at countrythunder.com/wi-lineup.

Songwriter’s Showcase

Country Thunder promoters said they are especially excited about the event’s news feature, the “Songwriter’s Showcase.”

“There will be a special tent on site that we’ve got and several Nashville songwriters coming in. And, what they’ll do is talk about the writing process,” said Kim Blevins, Country Thunder’s general manager. “Some of them have written No. 1 songs for other artists. So, we think it’s a pretty interesting thing.”

A total of eight songwriters will be in attendance, including Heath Warren, who wrote Zimmerman’s 2022 chart topping “Rock and a Hard Place” and Joe Fox, who penned John Pardi’s No. 1 hit, “Last Night Lonely”, also in 2022.

The songwriters will give concertgoers their insights and inspiration for how they produced lyrics and music for the songs, she said.

“And then, they’ll actually play the song,” she said. Songwriters will be performing unplugged with acoustic instruments and their voices, of course, for a more intimate engagement, organizers said.

The showcase, which made its debut at Country Thunder Arizona this year, is new to American audiences, she said. It will also be a feature at Country Thunder Florida in October.

“We’ve been doing it up in Canada (Saskatchewan and Alberta), our Canadian shows for several years, so we’re trying to incorporate it into all our shows in the U.S.,” she said.

Dance competition returns

Benoit said returning to the “Electric Thunder” tent this year, is “Dancing with the Thunder,” which includes lessons for line dancing and partners earlier on during the week and culminates on the final day with a dance competition and prizes.

“We’ll be bringing that back. It was a big success last year,” Benoit said. Among the prizes are some “highly sought-after belt buckles”, as well as tickets for next year’s concerts and camping on the grounds, she said.

Meanwhile, the Kenosha County Sheriff’s Department and event security officials have been coordinating over the last several months to ensure the safety of performers and concertgoers, alike.

Capt. Eric Klinkhammer, who has worked at the event for 30 years, overseeing ground command the last two years for the sheriff’s department, said he and his team of deputies and supervisors will be arriving early on Wednesday to prepare for arrivals.

“So, we’re there to handle anything that happens,” he said.

Wear your wristbands

This year, security will be especially watchful over the campgrounds, which were inundated with unauthorized visitors during the late-night hours due to some Country Thunder staffing issues last year, he said.

“The campgrounds were kind of open for anybody to come in and that kind of caused the problem. This year we’ve inspected it and they have the fencing up, they have security that’s going to be up at each gate,” Klinkhammer said. “And, you will have to have a four-day wristband in order to enter the campgrounds.”

Klinkhammer said he feels his officers and festival security are prepared for the upcoming event.

“Again, I’ll stress that we have things well at hand and we have plans if things go awry and we hope they don’t,” he said.

Additional information on ticketing, wristbands, maps for the parking, festival grounds and campgrounds along with policies and procedures can be found on the Country Thunder Wisconsin web page at countrythunder.com/wi.
